<li class="commentbody" id="comment-515673">
			<cite><a href='http://www.davidlebovitz.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>David</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-515673" title="">January 1, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">83</div>

				<p>AB: Powdered and/or confectioners sugar have miniscule (approximately 3%) amounts of a non-caking agent to keep it from clumping together. In the United States, it&#8217;s usually corn starch, and in France and other European countries, it has silicate (or the mineral tricalcium phosophate) added. I&#8217;ve done side-by-side tests and because it&#8217;s such a tiny quantity, they&#8217;re interchangeable in recipes like this where it&#8217;s going to be dissolved in liquids. You can also grind granulated sugar in a food processor until it&#8217;s powdery to make your own.</p>
<p>deb: Happy 2011!</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
